article.headline: Grizzlies drop fifth straight
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks are up to their old tricks. Without playing much defense around the basket, they're winning anyway by hitting their outside shots. Michael Finley was 5-of-7 on 3-pointers and the Mavs were 11-of-20 overall, helping them hold off the Memphis Grizzlies 104-98 Saturday night. "It's something we can't rely on," Finley said, "but the 3-point shot has to be a weapon." The Mavericks made their first four 3s and rolled to an early 17-point lead, but found themselves down four late in the second quarter. Dallas got back ahead by 18, then had to hold off the Grizzlies again in the final minutes. During a timeout with 4:51 left, the Grizzlies got a scare when 70-year-old coach Hubie Brown needed medical attention. He recovered quickly and remained on the bench the rest of the game. Although Brown insisted that he only tripped getting up from the bench, he was visited in the locker room by Mavericks assistant coach Donnie Nelson and one of Dallas' doctors. Brown resisted at first, then Nelson put his arm around Brown and he agreed to be examined in the training room. "When you're old, everybody gets excited," Brown said. "I just stumbled. I'm fine, everything is fine." The Grizzlies were playing for the fourth time in six days. This was their fifth straight loss, extending what already was their longest streak this season. Dallas, which ended a four-game skid by winning at Sacramento on Christmas, made 10 of its first 11 shots before its lack of an inside game became an issue. Memphis went on a 30-10 run behind easy layups, dunks, putbacks and short jumpers, mostly from Bonzi Wells, Lorenzen Wright, Bo Outlaw, Stromile Swift and Shane Battier -- all athletic players who thrive when they can drive the lane. The Mavericks regained the lead by halftime, scored the first 10 points of the second half and were in control until late. The Grizzlies got within 92-89 on a 3-pointer by Bonzi Wells, but Finley answered with another 3-pointer. A few minutes later, James Posey got the Grizzlies within five on a 3-pointer, and Steve Nash answered with a 3. Wells, who scored a season-high 30, missed a 3-pointer with 35.4 seconds left and Dallas leading 102-96. Memphis opted not to foul, and Finley made them pay by hitting a long jumper just before the shot clock expired. "It should've been easier," Nowitzki said. The Grizzlies finished with 60 points in the paint. The Mavericks were without two of their top interior defenders, Shawn Bradley (back spasms) and Eduardo Najera (sore knee), and Danny Fortson played just two minutes. As a result, Mavs coach Don Nelson tightened his rotation, limiting it mostly to his best scorers. Six players got at least 26 minutes and all responded with at least 14 points. Fortson (two minutes) and Tony Delk (seven minutes) getting the only remaining playing time. Nowitzki had 18 points and a season-high 17 rebounds, Steve Nash had 16 points and 10 assists and Antoine Walker had 13 points, 10 rebounds and eight assists to fall two assists shy of a triple-double for the second straight game. It's a tough pace for the long haul, but it could be exactly what Dallas needs right now. This started a stretch of five home games out of seven, and the Mavs are 13-2 at home. "This is a good time of year for us," Nowitzki said. "We need to turn it on. Everyone says it's early, but it's not." Wells, who was 12-of-26 off the bench, returned to Dallas for the first time since No. 17, when he was with Portland. An argument with coach Maurice Cheeks during that game led to his demotion and eventual trade to Memphis on Dec. 3. Pau Gasol, who scored at least 20 the last three games, had only 10. Posey and Wright both scored 14, with Wright grabbing 12 rebounds. Game notes
The Mavs have beaten the Grizzles six straight at home and 15 of 17. Dallas has scored at least 100 in the last nine meetings. ... With Memphis scoring 53 points in the first half, the Mavericks have given up at least 51 by halftime in 11 straight games. ... The Grizzlies (15-15) are at .500 for the first time since they were 8-8. The franchise had never been over the break-even point this late in a season. ... The Oklahoma State and Ole Miss football teams, in town for the Cotton Bowl, attended the game.
